Mittwoch, September 19
 
The smell of rain anywhere in the world is apparently the same, and I can think of nothing better.

I was thinking the other day that I'll need a journal in Germany, someplace where friends can keep track of me a little bit. And here it is, after 2 and a half years and one post, I'll resurrect something I tried to start a while ago. Hopefully I can keep with it this time. Posts forthcoming.

ATTN: When reading this story, if you have it, play Radiohead - Pyramid Song There is a very old section of buildings on the University of Denver campus, including Margery Reed Hall, University Hall, the Iliff School of theology, and lastly Mary Reed Hall. Mary Reed Hall was originally a library, now housing administrative offices and our chancellor, and is named after Mary Reed who donated a substantial amount of money to the school. Margery Reed was her daughter. There have been many stories about the building, and from the first day I had class there I heard it was haunted. The custodians that work in the building repeatedly report locking all the doors in the middle of the night, and turning off the lights after cleaning the rooms. They then come back 20 minutes later or so and the lights are on. They're usually the same set of lights too. There is also a service elevator, directly behind administrative offices from the first to the third floor. The elevator has been said to run itself, heard by the people working in the offices, even in the middle of the night. The funny thing is, the elevator is right next to her portrait on the third floor, where the old library was. The old library has two main rooms, and this room with the portrait separates the two rooms. Each room has a fireplace and big gothic style windows, with many bookshelves still along the walls. The elevator goes down to the basement, where my class is held. The elevator is just down the hall from my classroom. Here's the classroom door. The room was locked when I went back to get pictures, but there are big windows to the front of the building, and a very short fence, with a space in front of the windows. So I jumped the small fence down to the windows to get this picture of the inside of the classroom. The story our teacher told us at the beginning of class today is the biggest evidence in the ghost story so far. My class meets there at 1pm, and the class before meets at 11am in the same basement classroom. My professor went to a staff meeting, and everyone had to present on what new things were going on in their classes. The professor with the 11am class stood up, and said that during his lecture this morning, he was in the middle of a lesson and all 16 faces of the kids in his class went white and they looked freaked out. He turned around and saw nothing. On the bookshelf to the right of the whiteboard, a book had been facing with its cover outwards, not placed between the other books, and slowly rotated so that its back cover was now facing the class. Every single kid said they saw the book spin around, and half the class was so freaked out they left the lecture.
